<h2><i>About the Author</i></h2>

<p><s>RENÉ DUBOS</s>, professor at The Rockefeller University in New York City, is a microbiologist and experimental pathologist who over twenty years ago was the first to demonstrate the feasibility of obtaining germ-fighting drugs from microbes. For his scientific contributions, Dr. Dubos has received many awards; most recently he was the recipient of the Arches of Science Award of the Pacific Science Center. He is well known as an author and lecturer as well as a scientific investigator; his books include: <i>Louis Pasteur—Free Lance of Science</i>, <i>The Torch of Life</i>, <i>The Unseen World</i>, <i>The Dreams of Reason</i>, <i>The White Plague</i> (with Jean Dubos), <i>The Mirage of Health</i>, and <i>Man Adapting</i>. He was awarded a Pulitzer Prize in 1969 for <i>So Human an Animal</i>.</p>

