<h2>(Back cover)</h2>

<h3>So Human an Animal</h3>

<p>A renowned biologist tells how man is shaped by his environment, how we can control such environmental forces as urbanization and technology, and how we need urgently to study the effects of these forces if we are to enhance our humanness.</p>

<p>“Perhaps the most important message of our times, for all men, but for our own society and nation in particular... a work that must be read and reread.... It is, indeed, a work of scientific humanism, in the truest sense.”—Caryl P. Haskins, <i>The Virginia Quarterly Review</i></p>

<p>“[<i>So Human an Animal</i>] is likely to have an impact on society similar to, or greater than, Rachel Carson’s <i>Silent Spring</i> or John Kenneth Galbraith’s <i>The New Industrial State.</i> It is a timely contribution, beautifully written, and it will be read eagerly by all who are deeply disturbed and concerned with the present ecological crisis.”—Helmut K. Buechner, <i>Natural History</i></p>

